06967nam a22009375i 9780857459657DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013005541  a97808574596577 a10.1515/97808574596572doi  a(DE-B1597)635727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aGN345b.T73 2013 4aGN345b.T73 2013 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a30622300aTranscultural Montage /ced. by Rane Willerslev, Christian Suhr. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION Montage as an Amplifier of Invisibility -- tPART I Montage as an Analytic -- tCHAPTER 1 Montage and Time Deleuze, Cinema, and a Buddhist Sorcery Rite -- tCHAPTER 2 Temporal Aesthetics On Deleuzian Montage in Anthropology -- tCHAPTER 3 All the Difference in the World Liminality, Montage, and the Reinvention of Comparative Anthropology -- tCHAPTER 4 Into the Gloaming A Montage of the Senses -- tPART II Montage in Writing -- tCHAPTER 5 Being a Montage -- tCHAPTER 6 Smith’s Tour Favela -- tCHAPTER 7 Labor Days A Non-Linear Narrative of Development -- tCHAPTER 8 Mind the Gap -- tPART III Montage in Film -- tCHAPTER 9 Women in Cities Comparative Modernities and Cinematic Space in the 1930s -- tCHAPTER 10 Radioglaz and the Global City Possibilities and Constraints of Experimental Montage -- tCHAPTER 11 Filming in the Light of Memory -- tCHAPTER 12 Montage as Analysis in Ethnographic and Documentary Filmmaking From Hunting for Plots Toward Weaving Baskets of Data -- tCHAPTER 13 In Defense of Observational Cinema The Significance of the Bazinian Turn for Ethnographic Filmmaking -- tPART IV Montage in Museum Exhibitions -- tCHAPTER 14 Assembling Potentials, Mounting Effects Ethnographic Exhibitions Beyond Correspondence -- tCHAPTER 15 Assembling Bodies Cuts, Clusters, and Juxtapositions -- tCHAPTER 16 Project Villa Sovietica Clashing Images, Expectations, and Receptions -- tAFTERWORD The Traffic In Montage, Then and Now -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe disruptive power of montage has often been regarded as a threat to scholarly representations of the social world. This volume asserts the opposite: that the destabilization of commonsense perception is the very precondition for transcending social and cultural categories. The contributors—anthropologists, filmmakers, photographers, and curators—explore the use of montage as a heuristic tool for comparative analysis in anthropological writing, film, and exhibition making. Exploring phenomena such as human perception, memory, visuality, ritual, time, and globalization, they apply montage to restructure our basic understanding of social reality. Furthermore, as George E. Marcus suggests in the afterword, the power of montage that this volume exposes lies in its ability to open the very “combustion chamber” of social theory by juxtaposing one’s claims to knowledge with the path undertaken to arrive at those claims.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEthnologyxAuthorship. 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 0aMotion pictures in ethnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAntick, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinter, Julia T. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjerregaard, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalsgaard, Anne Line, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmpson, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb